_as_of = January 2016\n|population_footnotes = <ref>{{citation|title=\u6b77\u5e74\u4eba\u53e3\u7d71\u8a08 (Historical population figures) |language=Chinese |publisher=Zhonghe District Government |url=http://www.zhonghe.ris.ntpc.gov.tw/_file/1176/SG/24977/39037.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120805012648/http://www.zhonghe.ris.ntpc.gov.tw/_file/1176/SG/24977/39037.html |archivedate=August 5, 2012 }}</ref>\n|population_note =\n|population_total = 414,356\n|population_density_km2 =\n|population_density_sq_mi =\n|population_metro =\n|population_density_metro_km2 =\n|population_density_metro_sq_mi =\n|population_urban =\n|population_density_urban_km2 =\n|population_density_urban_sq_mi =\n|population_blank1_title =\n|population_blank1 =\n|population_density_blank1_km2 =\n|population_density_blank1_sq_mi =\n<!-- General information --------------->\n|timezone = [[Chungyuan Standard Time|CST]]\n|utc_offset = +8\n|timezone_DST =\n|utc_offset_DST =\n|coordinates = {{coord|24|59|50|N|121|30|15|E|region:TW|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation_footnotes = <!--for references: use <ref> </ref> tags-->\n|elevation_m =\n|elevation_ft =\n<!-- Area/postal codes & others -------->\n|postal_code_type = Postal code\n|postal_code = 235\n|area_code =\n|blank_name =\n|blank_info =\n|blank1_name =\n|blank1_info =\n|website = http://www.zhonghe.ntpc.gov.tw\n|footnotes =\n}}\n{{Chinese\n|title=Zhonghe District\n|c=\u4e2d\u548c\u5340\n|j=zong<sup>1</sup> wo<sup>4</sup> si<sup>5</sup>\n|p=Zh\u014dngh\u00e9 Q\u016b\n|tp=Jhongh\u00e9 Cyu\n|gr=Jongher Chiu\n|bpmf=\u3113\u3128\u3125 \u310f\u311c\u02ca \u3111\u3129\n|mps=J\u016bngh\u00e9 Chiu\n|poj=Tiong-h\u00f4 Khu\n|h=Zung<sup>1</sup>-fo<sup>2</sup> Sii<sup>5</sup>\n}}\n\n'''Zhonghe District''' ({{zh|c=\u4e2d\u548c\u5340|hp=Zh\u014dngh\u00e9 Q\u016b|tp=Jhongh\u00e9 Cyu}}, [[Pe\u030dh-\u014de-j\u012b]]: Tiong-h\u00f4 Khu), also spelled '''Chung-Ho''' and '''Jhonghe''', is an inner city district in an urban area in northern [[Taiwan]] ([[Republic of China]]).\n\n==Geography and climate==\nZhonghe lies just south-west of [[Taipei|Taipei City]] and shares borders with [[Banqiao District|Banqiao]], [[Xindian District|Xindian]], [[Tucheng District|Tucheng]] and [[Yonghe District|Yonghe]] Districts of [[New Taipei City]], as well as Taipei City. The average annual temperature is {{convert|21.7|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}} and the precipitation averages {{convert|2,111|mm|in}} per year. Most of Zhonghe lies a few tens of meters above sea level and is heavily urbanized, with forested hillier country in the southeast. A mountainous ridge forms most of the eastern border with Xindian, which includes the highest point in Zhonghe, the 302-meter Fenglusai ({{zh|t=\u98a8\u7210\u585e\u5c71|p=F\u0113ngl\u00fas\u00e0i Sh\u0101n}}).<ref>{{citation|isbn=978-986009391-9|title=\u53f0\u5317\u7e23\u4e2d\u548c\u5e02\u884c\u653f\u5340\u57df\u5716 (Jhonghe, Taipei County)|publisher=Ministry of the Interior|year=2007}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe present-day area of Zhonghe District was originally settled by [[Taiwanese aborigines|aboriginal tribes]]. During conflict between the colonial forces of the Dutch and the Spanish, the area is recorded by the Dutch as '''Chiron''', from the name of one of the tribes living there.<ref>{{cite book |script-title=zh:\u8af8\u7f85\u7e23\u5fd7 |trans-title=Zhuluo County Annals |language=zh}}</ref> This name is preserved in one of the constituent villages of the city, called ''Xiulang Li'' ({{lang|zh|\u79c0\u6717\u91cc}}), and the bridge which connects Zhonghe to Xindian.\n\nThe area was subsequently settled by [[Han Chinese]] migrants from [[Fujian]] but remained relatively unimportant until the end of the [[Second World War]]. In 1946 the population of the area of present-day Zhonghe and [[Yonghe District|Yonghe]] was 30,000 and it was classified as a [[township (Republic of China)|rural township]].<ref name=\"History\">{{cite web|url=http://www.junghe.tpc.gov.tw/History.aspx |title=History |publisher=Zhonghe City Government |accessdate=2008-07-18 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080313054333/http://www.junghe.tpc.gov.tw/History.aspx |archivedate=2008-03-13 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nDue to rapid population growth Yonghe was separated from Zhonghe in 1958. Subsequently, on January 1, 1979, Zhonghe was upgraded to [[county-controlled city]] status after reaching a population of 170,000.<ref name=\"History\" /> On 25 December 2010, due to the changing from Taipei [[County (Taiwan)|County]] to New Taipei [[Special municipality (Taiwan)|City]], Zhonghe City was changed to Zhonghe [[District (Taiwan)|District]].\n\n==Administrative divisions==\nZhonghe is divided into 93 villages, which are further subdivided into ''l\u00edn'' ({{zh|c=\u9130|l=neighbourhoods|labels=no}}), of which there are 2,972 in total. Some administration is shared with neighbouring Yonghe District; due to both this and their proximity, they are sometimes collectively known as '''Shuanghe''' ({{zh|c=\u96d9\u548c|l=Twin ''He''|labels=no}}). This is also reflected in the names of various institutions such as Shuang-Ho Hospital<ref>{{citation|url=http://enoffical.shh.org.tw/enUI/A/A10100.aspx|title=About SHH|publisher=Shuang Ho Hospital|access-date=2012-08-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130817083959/http://enoffical.shh.org.tw/enUI/A/A10100.aspx|archive-date=2013-08-17|url-status=dead}}</ref> in Zhonghe and Shuanghe Libai Church<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.shchurch.org.tw/ezportal/homeweb/catalog.php?infoscatid=17|language=Chinese|script-title=zh:\u672c\u5802\u7c21\u4ecb |trans-title=Introduction to the Church |publisher=Shuanghe Libai Church}}</ref> in Yonghe.\n\n==Transportation==\n\n===Rail===\nZhonghe is served by the [[Zhonghe\u2013Xinlu line]] of the [[Taipei Metro]], three stations of which are located in the city: [[Yongan Market station|Yongan Market]], [[Jingan station|Jingan]] and the terminal station, [[Nanshijiao station|Nanshijiao]]. Scheduled to begin operation in June 2018, the [[Circular line (Taipei Metro)|Circular line]] will add a further five metro stations in Zhonghe, and transform Jingan Station into an interchange station between the Circular and Zhonghe lines. Further into the future, the [[Wanda line]] and the North-South section of the [[Yellow line (Taipei Metro)|Yellow line]] will eventually bring the number of MRT stations in Zhonghe to fifteen. The closest regular rail and high-speed services are from [[Banqiao station]] in neighbouring [[Banqiao District]].\n\n===Road===\nZhonghe has an interchange on one of Taiwan's two main north-south road arteries; the [[National Highway 3 (Taiwan)|National Highway 3]]. Also providing road links is [[Provincial Highway No. 64 (Taiwan)|Provincial Highway 64]], an elevated expressway that cuts through the middle of the district, with several on and off-ramps in Zhonghe itself. There are two bridges over the [[Xindian River]]; Xiulang Bridge, which connects Zhonghe with [[Xindian District|Xindian]], and Huazhong Bridge, reaching [[Taipei]]'s [[Wanhua District]].\n\n==Education==\nZhonghe is home to the [[National Taiwan Library]], which is located in the grounds of the [[Second Taiwan Strait Crisis|8-23]] Memorial Park. It has one of the best collections in Taiwan of factual books about Taiwan in English.\n\nThere are nine elementary schools, five junior high schools, four senior high schools (2 public and 2 private high schools) in Zhonghe. The [[Hwa Hsia University of Technology]] is also located in the city.<ref>https://www.zhonghe.ntpc.gov.tw/content/?parent_id=10236</ref>\n\n* [[Zhonghe Elementary School]]\n* [[Guangfu Elementary School]]\n* [[Fuxing Elementary School]]\n* [[Jingxin Elementary School]]\n* [[Xiushan Elementary School]]\n* [[Jisui Elementary School]]\n* [[Ziqiang Elementary School]]\n* [[Xingnan Elementary School]]\n* [[Jinhe Elementary School]]\n\n* [[Zhonghe Junior High School]]\n* [[Zhanghe Junior High School]]\n* [[Jisui Junior High School]]\n* [[Ziqiang Junior High School]]\n* [[Jinhe High School]]\n\n* [[Jinhe High School]]\n* [[Chung Ho Senior High School]]\n* [[Private NanShan Senior High School]]\n* [[Private Chu-Lin Senior High School]]\n\n==Economy==\nThe offices of a number of technology companies are located in the district, including the [[Asia-Pacific]] head office of [[Viewsonic]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.viewsonic.com/contactus/locations.htm |title=Locations |publisher=Viewsonic |accessdate=2008-07-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080801134846/http://www.viewsonic.com/contactus/locations.htm |archivedate=August 1, 2008 }}</ref> SpotCam,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.myspotcam.com/welcome/contact/|title=Contact SpotCam|publisher=SpotCam|accessdate=2016-04-03}}</ref> a [[Texas Instruments]] research facility,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://focus.ti.com/general/docs/gencontent.tsp?contentId=29893|title=TI Worldwide Sales & Support Offices|publisher=Texas Instruments|accessdate=2008-07-27}}</ref> the head offices of Cooler Master,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.coolermaster.com/contactus/contactus.php?language=en&id=5#tw |title=Contact Us |publisher=Cooler Master |accessdate=2008-08-09 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080526013532/http://www.coolermaster.com/contactus/contactus.php?language=en&id=5#tw |archivedate=2008-05-26 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and [[Micro-Star International]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://global.msi.com.tw/index.php?func=html&name=aboutus |title=About Us |publisher=Micro-Star International |accessdate=2008-08-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080808222143/http://global.msi.com.tw/index.php?func=html&name=aboutus |archivedate=August 8, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==Cultural and religious sites==\n* Hongludi Temple\n* Yuantong Temple\n* Xingnan Night Market\n* Fangliao Night Market\n\n===Burma Street===\n'''Huaxin Street''' (\u83ef\u65b0\u8857), near [[Nanshijiao Station|Nanshijiao MRT Station]], is home to a large proportion of Taiwan's small [[Burma|Burmese]] immigrant population. Zhonghe District is home to 40,000 [[Burmese Chinese]] (2008), making up 10% of Zhonghe's population, and constituting one of the largest communities of Burmese Chinese outside of Burma.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Lu|first=Hsin-chun Tasaw|year=2008|title=Festivalizing Thingyan, Negotiating Ethnicity: Burmese Chinese Migrants in Taiwan|journal=Journal of Burma Studies|volume=12|pages=30|url=http://muse.jhu.edu/journals/journal_of_burma_studies/v012/12.lu.html|doi=10.1353/jbs.2008.0001}}</ref> Consequently, there are numerous stores and restaurants in this area selling Burmese produce and there are also cultural events on occasion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amcham.com.tw/publication_topics_view.php?volume=38&vol_num=1&topics_id=1016 |title=Tapping the Grapevine |publisher=American Chamber of Commerce |accessdate=2008-07-16 }} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\n<gallery class=\"center\">\nImage:Zhonghe 8-23 park.jpg|Archway in the 8-23 Park\nImage:Tudi Gong (1).jpg|Statue of Tudi Gong at Hongludi Temple\nImage:Trees in Zhonghe.jpg|Trees in the 8-23 Park\nImage:National Taiwan Library entry 2005.jpg|National Taiwan Library\nImage:Jingsin Elementary School.jpg|Jingxin Elementary School\nImage:Singnan Night Market.jpg|Xingnan Night Market Entrance\nImage:Side Of Jingping Road.jpg|Jingping Road\nImage:Nanshijiao Station.JPG|Nanshijiao Station, southern terminus of the MRT's [[Zhonghe Line]]\nImage:Yuantong Temple.jpg|Yuantong Temple ([[Buddhism|Buddhist]])\nFile:Jhonghe.jpg|High-rise office buildings\n\n</gallery>\n\n==Famous natives==\n* Lin Ching-i - [[Chinese Taipei]] women's volleyball player\n\n==International relations==\n{{Main|List of twin towns and sister cities in Taiwan (Republic of China)}}\n\n===Twin towns \u2014 sister cities===\nZhonghe, Taiwan is [[town twinning|twinned]] with:\n* [[Image:Flag of the United States.svg|20px]] [[Los Gatos]], [[California]], [[United States]]<ref>[http://www.svcn.com/archives/lgwt/02.27.02/sistercity-0209.html Los Gatos Weekly-Times | Monte Sereno Sister City<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Zhonghe District, New Taipei}}\n{{Wikivoyage|Zhonghe}}\n\n* [http://www.zhonghe.ntpc.gov.tw/ Government website] {{in lang|zh}}\n* [http://www.zhonghe.ntpc.gov.tw/Accessibility.aspx Government website]{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} \n* [https://www.panoramio.com/photo/4060143 View of Zhonghe District]\n\n{{Districts in Taiwan}}\n\n[[Category:Zhonghe District| ]]\n", "name_user": "Wbm1058", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRail", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zhonghe_District"}
{"title_page": "Monin\u2013Obukhov similarity theory", "text_new": "{{technical|date=June 2014}}\n\n'''Monin\u2013Obukhov (M\u2013O) similarity theory''' describes non-dimensionalized mean flow and mean temperature in the [[surface layer]] under non-neutral conditions as a function of the dimensionless height parameter,<ref name=mo54>{{cite journal|last=Monin|first=A. S.|author2=Obukhov, A. M.|title=Basic laws of turbulent mixing in the surface layer of the atmosphere|journal=Tr. Akad. Nauk. SSSR Geophiz. Inst.|date=1954|volume=24|issue=151|pages=163\u2013187}}</ref> named after Russian scientists [[Andrei Monin|A. S. Monin]] and [[Alexander Obukhov|A. M. Obukhov]]. Similarity theory is an empirical method which describes universal relationships between non-dimensionalized variables of fluids based on the [[Buckingham \u03c0 theorem|Buckingham Pi theorem]]. Similarity theory is extensively used in boundary layer meteorology, since relations in turbulent processes are not always resolvable from first principles.<ref name=s88>{{cite book|last=Stull|first=Roland|title=An introduction to boundary layer meteorology|date=1988|publisher=Springer|location=Netherlands|isbn=978-94-009-3027-8}}</ref>\n\nAn idealized vertical profile of the mean flow for a neutral boundary layer is the [[logarithmic wind profile]] derived from [[Ludwig Prandtl|Prandtl]]'s [[Mixing length model|mixing length theory]],<ref name=p25>{{cite journal|last=Prandtl|first=Ludwig|title=Bericht \u00fcber Untersuchungen zur ausgebildeten Turbulenz|journal=Zeitschrift f\u00fcr Angewandte Mathematik und Mechanik|volume=5|issue=2|pages=136\u2013139}}</ref> which states that the horizontal component of mean flow is proportional to the logarithm of height. M\u2013O similarity theory further generalizes the mixing length theory in non-neutral conditions by using so-called \"universal functions\" of dimensionless height to characterize vertical distributions of mean flow and temperature. The Obukhov length (<math>L</math>), a characteristic length scale of surface layer turbulence derived by Obukhov in 1946,<ref name=o71/> is used for non-dimensional scaling of the actual height. M\u2013O similarity theory marked a significant landmark of modern [[Microscale meteorology|micrometeorology]], providing a theoretical basis for micrometerological experiments and measurement techniques.<ref name=f06>{{cite journal|last=Foken|first=T.|title=50 Years of the Monin-Obukhov similarity theory|journal=Boundary-Layer Meteorology|volume=2|pages=7\u201329|accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n== The Obukhov length ==\nThe Obukhov length <math>L</math> is a length parameter for the surface layer in the [[boundary layer]], which characterizes the relative contributions to [[Turbulence kinetic energy|turbulent kinetic energy]] from buoyant production and shear production. The Obukhov length was formulated using Richardson's criterion for dynamic stability.<ref name=o71>{{cite journal|last=Obukhov|first=A. M.|title=Turbulence in an atmosphere with a non-uniform temperature|journal=Boundary-Layer Meteorology|date=1971|volume=2|issue=1|pages=7\u201329|doi=10.1007/BF00718085|bibcode = 1971BoLMe...2....7O }}</ref> It was derived as,\n\n<math>\nL=-\\dfrac{u_*^3}{\\kappa \\dfrac{g}{T}\\dfrac{Q}{\\rho c_p}}\n</math>\n\nwhere <math>\\kappa\\approx 0.40</math> is the [[von K\u00e1rm\u00e1n constant]], <math>u_*</math> [[Shear velocity|friction velocity]], <math>Q</math> turbulent [[heat flux]], and <math>c_p</math> heat capacity.<ref name=o71 />  Virtual [[potential temperature]] <math>\\theta_v</math> is often used instead of temperature <math>T</math> to correct for the effects of pressure and water vapor. <math>Q</math> can be written as vertical eddy flux,\n\n<math>\nQ=\\rho c_p \\overline{w'\\theta_v'}\n</math>\n\nwith <math>w'</math> and <math>\\theta_v'</math> perturbations of vertical velocity and virtual potential temperature, respectively. Therefore, the Obukhov length can also be defined as,<ref name=f08>{{cite book|last=Foken|first=Thomas|title=Micrometeorology|date=2008|publisher=Springer-Verlag|isbn=978-3-540-74665-2|pages=42\u201349}}</ref>\n\n<math>\nL=-\\dfrac{u_*^3}{\\kappa \\dfrac{g}{\\overline{\\theta_v}}\\overline{w'\\theta_v'}}\n</math>\n\nThe Obukhov length also acts as a criterion for the static stability of surface layer. When <math>L<0</math>, the surface layer is statically unstable, and when <math>L>0</math> the surface layer is statically stable. The absolute magnitude of <math>L</math> indicates the deviation from statically neutral state, with smaller <math>|L|</math> values corresponding to larger deviations from neutral conditions. When <math>|L|</math> is small and <math>L<0</math>, buoyant processes dominate the production of turbulent kinetic energy compared with shear production. By definition, under neutral conditions <math>L\\rightarrow\\infty</math>. \nThe Obukhov length <math>L</math> is used for non-dimensionalization of height <math>z</math> in similarity theory.\n\n== Governing formulae for similarity relations ==\nM\u2013O similarity theory parameterizes fluxes in the surface layer as a function of the dimensionless length parameter <math>\\zeta=z/L</math>. From [[Buckingham \u03c0 theorem|the Buckingham Pi theorem]] of dimensional analysis, two dimensionless group can be formed from the basic parameter set <math>\\{ u_*, g/\\overline{\\theta_v}, \\partial\\overline{u}/\\partial z, z, \\overline{w'\\theta_v'}\\}</math>,\n\n<math>\n\\dfrac{\\kappa z}{u_*}\\dfrac{\\partial \\overline{u}}{\\partial z}\n</math>, and \n<math>\n\\zeta =\\dfrac{z}{L}\n</math>\n\nFrom there, a function <math>\\varphi_M(\\zeta)</math> can be determined to empirically describe the relationship between the two dimensionless quantities, called a universal function. Similarly, <math>\\varphi_H(\\zeta)</math> can be defined for the dimensionless group of mean temperature profile. \nMean wind and temperature profiles therefore satisfy the following relations,<ref name = mo54/><ref name = f06/>\n\n<math>\n\\dfrac{\\partial \\overline{u}}{\\partial z} =\\dfrac{u_*}{\\kappa z}\\varphi_M(\\zeta)\n</math>\n\n<math>\n\\dfrac{\\partial \\overline{\\theta_v}}{\\partial z} =\\dfrac{\\theta_*}{\\kappa z}\\varphi_H(\\zeta)\n</math>\n\nwhere <math>\\theta_*= - \\dfrac{\\overline{w'\\theta_v'}}{u_*}</math> is the characteristic dynamical temperature, <math>\\varphi_M</math> and <math>\\varphi_H</math> are the universal functions of momentum and heat. The [[Eddy diffusion|eddy diffusivity]] coefficients for momentum and heat fluxes are defined as follows,\n\n<math>\nK_M = \\kappa z\\dfrac{ u_*}{\\varphi_M(\\zeta)},\\ K_H = \\kappa z\\dfrac{ u_*}{\\varphi_H(\\zeta)}\n</math>\n\n<math>K_M</math> and <math>K_H</math> can be related with the [[turbulent Prandtl number]] <math>Pr_t</math>,\n\n<math>\n\\dfrac{K_H}{K_M}=\\dfrac{1}{Pr_t}>1\n</math>\n\nIn reality, the universal functions need to be determined using experimental data when applying M\u2013O similarity theory. Although the choice of universal functions is not unique, certain functional forms have been proposed and are widely accepted for fitting experimental data.\n\n== Universal functions of the Monin-Obukhov similarity theory ==\n\n[[File:Universal functions for Monin-Obukhov similarity theory.png|thumb|right|500px|Universal functions for Monin-Obukhov similarity theory]]\n\nSeveral functional forms have been proposed to represent the universal functions of similarity theory. Because the Obukhov length is determined when <math>L\\Big(\\dfrac{\\partial Ri}{\\partial z}\\Big)_{z=0}=1</math>, where <math>Ri</math> is the [[Richardson number]], the following condition must be satisfied by the universal function chosen,<ref name=mo54/>\n\n<math>\n\\varphi(0)=1\n</math>\n\nA first order approximation of the universal function for momentum flux is,\n\n<math>\n\\varphi_M(\\zeta)=1+\\beta\\zeta\n</math>\n\nwhere <math>\\beta\\approx 6</math>.<ref name=f06/> However this is only applicable when <math>0<\\zeta<1</math>. For conditions where <math>\\zeta<0</math>, the relation is,\n\n<math>\n\\varphi_M^4-\\gamma\\zeta\\varphi_M^3=1\n</math>\n\nwhere <math>\\gamma</math> is a coefficient to be determined from experimental data. This equation can be further approximated by <math>\\varphi_M=(1+\\gamma\\zeta)^{-1/4}</math> when <math>-2<\\zeta<0</math>.\n\nBased on the results of the 1968 Kansas experiment, the following universal functions are determined for horizontal mean flow and mean virtual potential temperature,<ref name=b71>{{cite journal|last=Businger|first=J. A.|author-link1=Joost Businger|author2=J. C. Wyngaard |author3=Y. Izumi |author4=E. F. Bradley |title=Flux-profile relationships in the atmospheric surface layer|journal=Journal of the Atmospheric Sciences|date=1971|volume=28|issue=2|pages=181\u2013189|bibcode = 1971JAtS...28..181B |doi = 10.1175/1520-0469(1971)028<0181:FPRITA>2.0.CO;2 }}</ref>\n\n<math>\n\\varphi_M(\\zeta)=(1-15\\zeta)^{-1/4}\\quad -2<\\zeta <0\n</math>\n\n<math>\n\\varphi_M(\\zeta)=1+4.7\\zeta\\quad 0<\\zeta <1\n</math>\n\n<math>\n\\varphi_H(\\zeta)=0.74(1-9\\zeta)^{-1/2}\\quad  -2<\\zeta <0\n</math>\n\n<math>\n\\varphi_H(\\zeta)=0.74+4.7\\zeta\\quad 0<\\zeta <1\n</math>\n\nOther methods which determine the universal functions using the relation between <math>\\zeta</math> and <math>Ri</math> are also used.<ref name=a01>{{cite book|last=Arya|first=S. P.|title=Introduction to Micrometeorology|date=2001|publisher=Academic Press|location=San Diego}}</ref><ref name=h88>{{cite journal|last=H\u00f6gstr\u00f6m|first=U.|title=Non-dimensional wind and temperature profiles in the atmospheric surface layer: A re-evaluation|journal=Boundary-Layer Meteorology|date=1988|volume=42|issue=1\u20132|pages=55\u201378|bibcode = 1988BoLMe..42...55H |doi = 10.1007/BF00119875 }}</ref>\n\nFor sublayers with significant roughness, e.g. vegetated surfaces or urban areas, the universal functions must be modified to include the effects of surface roughness.<ref name=f08/>\n\n== Validations ==\nA myriad of experimental efforts were devoted to validation of the M-O similarity theory. Field observations and computer simulations have generally demonstrated that M-O similarity theory is well satisfied.\n\n=== In field measurements ===\n[[File:Rice County P5310407.JPG|350px|thumbnail|right|A Kansas wheat field]]\nThe 1968 Kansas experiment found great consistency between measurements and predictions from similarity relations for the entire range of stability values.<ref name = b71/> A flat wheat field in Kansas served as the experiment site, with winds measured by anemometers mounted at different heights on a 32 m tower. The temperature profile was also measured in a similar manner. Results from the Kansas field study indicated that the ratio of eddy diffusivities of heat and momentum was approximately 1.35 under neutral conditions. A similar experiment was conducted in a flat field in northwestern Minnesota in 1973. This experiment used both ground and balloon-based observations of the surface layer and further validated the theoretical predictions from similarity.<ref name=k76>{{cite journal|last=Kaimal|first=J. C.|author2=J. C. Wyngaard |author3=D. A. Haugen |author4=O. R. Cot\u00e9 |author5=Y. Izumi |author6=S. J. Caughey |author7=C. J. Readings |title=Turbulence Structure in the Convective Boundary Layer|journal=Journal of the Atmospheric Sciences|date=1976|volume=33|issue=11|pages=2152\u20132169|bibcode = 1976JAtS...33.2152K |doi = 10.1175/1520-0469(1976)033<2152:TSITCB>2.0.CO;2 }}</ref>\n\n=== In large eddy simulations ===\nIn addition to field experiments, analysis of M\u2013O similarity theory can be conducted using high-resolution [[large eddy simulation]]s. The simulation indicates that the temperature field agrees well with M\u2013O similarity. However, the velocity field shows significant anomalies from M\u2013O similarity.<ref name=les_mo>{{cite journal|last1=Khanna|first1=Samir|last2=Brasseur|first2=James G.|title=Analysis of Monin\u2013Obukhov similarity from large-eddy simulation|journal=J. Fluid Mech.|date=1997|volume=345|issue=1|pages=251\u2013286|bibcode = 1997JFM...345..251K }}</ref>\n\n== Limitations ==\nM\u2013O similarity theory, albeit successful for surface layers from experimental validations, is essentially a diagnostic empirical theory based upon local first order turbulence closure. Typically, 10%~20% errors are associated with the universal functions. When applied to a vegetated areas or complex terrains, it can result in large discrepancies. Because universal functions are often determined under dry conditions, the applicability of M\u2013O similarity theory under moist conditions were not well studied.\n\nBasic parameter set of the M\u2013O similarity theory includes buoyancy production <math>\\dfrac{gQ}{T}</math>. It is argued that with such parameter set, the scaling is applied to the integral features of the flow, whereas an eddy specific similarity relationship prefers the usage of energy [[dissipation]] rate <math>\\epsilon_0</math>.<ref name=m09>{{cite journal|last=McNaughton|first=Keith|title=The rise and fall of Monin-Obukhov theory|journal=AsiaFlux Newsletter|date=2009|issue=30|pages=1\u20134|url=http://www.mcnaughty.com/keith/papers/Rise_and_Fall_of_MOST.pdf}}</ref> This scheme is able to explain anomalies of M\u2013O similarity theory, but involves non-locality to modeling and experiments.\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Monin\u2013Obukhov length|Obukhov length]]\n*[[Surface layer]]\n*[[Log wind profile|Logarithmic wind profile]]\n*[[Mixing length model]]\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Monin-Obukhov similarity theory}}\n[[Category:Dimensional analysis]]\n[[Category:Physics theorems]]\n", "text_old": "{{technical|date=June 2014}}\n\n'''Monin\u2013Obukhov (M\u2013O) similarity theory''' describes non-dimensionalized mean flow and mean temperature in the [[surface layer]] under non-neutral conditions as a function of the dimensionless height parameter,<ref name=mo54>{{cite journal|last=Monin|first=A. S.|author2=Obukhov, A. M.|title=Basic laws of turbulent mixing in the surface layer of the atmosphere|journal=Tr. Akad. Nauk. SSSR Geophiz. Inst.|date=1954|volume=24|issue=151|pages=163\u2013187}}</ref> named after Russian scientists [[Andrei Monin|A. S. Monin]] and [[Alexander Obukhov|A. M. Obukhov]]. Similarity theory is an empirical method which describes universal relationships between non-dimensionalized variables of fluids based on the [[Buckingham \u03c0 theorem|Buckingham Pi theorem]]. Similarity theory is extensively used in boundary layer meteorology, since relations in turbulent processes are not always resolvable from first principles.<ref name=s88>{{cite book|last=Stull|first=Roland|title=An introduction to boundary layer meteorology|date=1988|publisher=Springer|location=Netherlands|isbn=978-94-009-3027-8}}</ref>\n\nAn idealized vertical profile of the mean flow for a neutral boundary layer is the [[logarithmic wind profile]] derived from [[Ludwig Prandtl|Prandtl]]'s [[Mixing length model|mixing length theory]],<ref name=p25>{{cite journal|last=Prandtl|first=Ludwig|title=Bericht \u00fcber Untersuchungen zur ausgebildeten Turbulenz|journal=Zeitschrift f\u00fcr Angewandte Mathematik und Mechanik|volume=5|issue=2|pages=136\u2013139}}</ref> which states that the horizontal component of mean flow is proportional to the logarithm of height. M\u2013O similarity theory further generalizes the mixing length theory in non-neutral conditions by using so-called \"universal functions\" of dimensionless height to characterize vertical distributions of mean flow and temperature. The Obukhov length (<math>L</math>), a characteristic length scale of surface layer turbulence derived by Obukhov in 1946,<ref name=o71/> is used for non-dimensional scaling of the actual height. M\u2013O similarity theory marked a significant landmark of modern [[Microscale meteorology|micrometeorology]], providing a theoretical basis for micrometerological experiments and measurement techniques.<ref name=f06>{{cite journal|last=Foken|first=T.|title=50 Years of the Monin-Obukhov similarity theory|journal=Boundary-Layer Meteorology|volume=2|pages=7\u201329|accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n== The Obukhov length ==\nThe Obukhov length <math>L</math> is a length parameter for the surface layer in the [[boundary layer]], which characterizes the relative contributions to [[Turbulence kinetic energy|turbulent kinetic energy]] from buoyant production and shear production. The Obukhov length was formulated using Richardson's criterion for dynamic stability.<ref name=o71>{{cite journal|last=Obukhov|first=A. M.|title=Turbulence in an atmosphere with a non-uniform temperature|journal=Boundary-Layer Meteorology|date=1971|volume=2|issue=1|pages=7\u201329|doi=10.1007/BF00718085|bibcode = 1971BoLMe...2....7O }}</ref> It was derived as,\n\n<math>\nL=-\\dfrac{u_*^3}{\\kappa \\dfrac{g}{T}\\dfrac{Q}{\\rho c_p}}\n</math>\n\nwhere <math>\\kappa\\approx 0.40</math> is the [[von K\u00e1rm\u00e1n constant]], <math>u_*</math> [[Shear velocity|friction velocity]], <math>Q</math> turbulent [[heat flux]], and <math>c_p</math> heat capacity.<ref name=o71 />  Virtual [[potential temperature]] <math>\\theta_v</math> is often used instead of temperature <math>T</math> to correct for the effects of pressure and water vapor. <math>Q</math> can be written as vertical eddy flux,\n\n<math>\nQ=\\rho c_p \\overline{w'\\theta_v'}\n</math>\n\nwith <math>w'</math> and <math>\\theta_v'</math> perturbations of vertical velocity and virtual potential temperature, respectively. Therefore, the Obukhov length can also be defined as,<ref name=f08>{{cite book|last=Foken|first=Thomas|title=Micrometeorology|date=2008|publisher=Springer-Verlag|isbn=978-3-540-74665-2|pages=42\u201349}}</ref>\n\n<math>\nL=-\\dfrac{u_*^3}{\\kappa \\dfrac{g}{\\overline{\\theta_v}}\\overline{w'\\theta_v'}}\n</math>\n\nThe Obukhov length also acts as a criterion for the static stability of surface layer. When <math>L<0</math>, the surface layer is statically unstable, and when <math>L>0</math> the surface layer is statically stable. The absolute magnitude of <math>L</math> indicates the deviation from statically neutral state, with smaller <math>|L|</math> values corresponding to larger deviations from neutral conditions. When <math>|L|</math> is small and <math>L<0</math>, buoyant processes dominate the production of turbulent kinetic energy compared with shear production. By definition, under neutral conditions <math>L\\rightarrow\\infty</math>. \nThe Obukhov length <math>L</math> is used for non-dimensionalization of height <math>z</math> in similarity theory.\n\n== Governing formulae for similarity relations ==\nM\u2013O similarity theory parameterizes fluxes in the surface layer as a function of the dimensionless length parameter <math>\\zeta=z/L</math>. From [[Buckingham \u03c0 theorem|the Buckingham Pi theorem]] of dimensional analysis, two dimensionless group can be formed from the basic parameter set <math>\\{ u_*, g/\\overline{\\theta_v}, \\partial\\overline{u}/\\partial z, z, \\overline{w'\\theta_v'}\\}</math>,\n\n<math>\n\\dfrac{\\kappa z}{u_*}\\dfrac{\\partial \\overline{u}}{\\partial z}\n</math>, and \n<math>\n\\zeta =\\dfrac{z}{L}\n</math>\n\nFrom there, a function <math>\\varphi_M(\\zeta)</math> can be determined to empirically describe the relationship between the two dimensionless quantities, called a universal function. Similarly, <math>\\varphi_H(\\zeta)</math> can be defined for the dimensionless group of mean temperature profile. \nMean wind and temperature profiles therefore satisfy the following relations,<ref name = mo54/><ref name = f06/>\n\n<math>\n\\dfrac{\\partial \\overline{u}}{\\partial z} =\\dfrac{u_*}{\\kappa z}\\varphi_M(\\zeta)\n</math>\n\n<math>\n\\dfrac{\\partial \\overline{\\theta_v}}{\\partial z} =\\dfrac{\\theta_*}{\\kappa z}\\varphi_H(\\zeta)\n</math>\n\nwhere <math>\\theta_*= - \\dfrac{\\overline{w'\\theta_v'}}{u_*}</math> is the characteristic dynamical temperature, <math>\\varphi_M</math> and <math>\\varphi_H</math> are the universal functions of momentum and heat. The [[Eddy diffusion|eddy diffusivity]] coefficients for momentum and heat fluxes are defined as follows,\n\n<math>\nK_M = \\kappa z\\dfrac{ u_*}{\\varphi_M(\\zeta)},\\ K_H = \\kappa z\\dfrac{ u_*}{\\varphi_H(\\zeta)}\n</math>\n\n<math>K_M</math> and <math>K_H</math> can be related with the [[turbulent Prandtl number]] <math>Pr_t</math>,\n\n<math>\n\\dfrac{K_H}{K_M}=\\dfrac{1}{Pr_t}>1\n</math>\n\nIn reality, the universal functions need to be determined using experimental data when applying M\u2013O similarity theory. Although the choice of universal functions is not unique, certain functional forms have been proposed and are widely accepted for fitting experimental data.\n\n== Universal functions of the Monin-Obukhov similarity theory ==\n\n[[File:Universal functions for Monin-Obukhov similarity theory.png|thumb|right|500px|Universal functions for Monin-Obukhov similarity theory]]\n\nSeveral functional forms have been proposed to represent the universal functions of similarity theory. Because the Obukhov length is determined when <math>L\\Big(\\dfrac{\\partial Ri}{\\partial z}\\Big)_{z=0}=1</math>, where <math>Ri</math> is the [[Richardson number]], the following condition must be satisfied by the universal function chosen,<ref name=mo54/>\n\n<math>\n\\varphi(0)=1\n</math>\n\nA first order approximation of the universal function for momentum flux is,\n\n<math>\n\\varphi_M(\\zeta)=1+\\beta\\zeta\n</math>\n\nwhere <math>\\beta\\approx 6</math>.<ref name=f06/> However this is only applicable when <math>0<\\zeta<1</math>. For conditions where <math>\\zeta<0</math>, the relation is,\n\n<math>\n\\varphi_M^4-\\gamma\\zeta\\varphi_M^3=1\n</math>\n\nwhere <math>\\gamma</math> is a coefficient to be determined from experimental data. This equation can be further approximated by <math>\\varphi_M=(1+\\gamma\\zeta)^{-1/4}</math> when <math>-2<\\zeta<0</math>.\n\nBased on the results of the 1968 Kansas experiment, the following universal functions are determined for horizontal mean flow and mean virtual potential temperature,<ref name=b71>{{cite journal|last=Businger|first=J. A.|author-link1=Joost Businger|author2=J. C. Wyngaard |author3=Y. Izumi |author4=E. F. Bradley |title=Flux-profile relationships in the atmospheric surface layer|journal=Journal of the Atmospheric Sciences|date=1971|volume=28|issue=2|pages=181\u2013189|bibcode = 1971JAtS...28..181B |doi = 10.1175/1520-0469(1971)028<0181:FPRITA>2.0.CO;2 }}</ref>\n\n<math>\n\\varphi_M(\\zeta)=(1-15\\zeta)^{-1/4}\\quad -2<\\zeta <0\n</math>\n\n<math>\n\\varphi_M(\\zeta)=1+4.7\\zeta\\quad 0<\\zeta <1\n</math>\n\n<math>\n\\varphi_H(\\zeta)=0.74(1-9\\zeta)^{-1/2}\\quad  -2<\\zeta <0\n</math>\n\n<math>\n\\varphi_H(\\zeta)=0.74+4.7\\zeta\\quad 0<\\zeta <1\n</math>\n\nOther methods which determine the universal functions using the relation between <math>\\zeta</math> and <math>Ri</math> are also used.<ref name=a01>{{cite book|last=Arya|first=S. P.|title=Introduction to Micrometeorology|date=2001|publisher=Academic Press|location=San Diego}}</ref><ref name=h88>{{cite journal|last=H\u00f6gstr\u00f6m|first=U.|title=Non-dimensional wind and temperature profiles in the atmospheric surface layer: A re-evaluation|journal=Boundary-Layer Meteorology|date=1988|volume=42|issue=1\u20132|pages=55\u201378|bibcode = 1988BoLMe..42...55H |doi = 10.1007/BF00119875 }}</ref>\n\nFor sublayers with significant roughness, e.g. vegetated surfaces or urban areas, the universal functions must be modified to include the effects of surface roughness.<ref name=f08/>\n\n== Validations ==\nA myriad of experimental efforts were devoted to validation of the M-O similarity theory. Field observations and computer simulations have generally demonstrated that M-O similarity theory is well satisfied.\n\n=== In field measurements ===\n[[File:FEMA - 35029 - Kansas wheat field.jpg|350px|thumbnail|right|A typical Kansas wheat field]]\nThe 1968 Kansas experiment found great consistency between measurements and predictions from similarity relations for the entire range of stability values.<ref name = b71/> A flat wheat field in Kansas served as the experiment site, with winds measured by anemometers mounted at different heights on a 32 m tower. The temperature profile was also measured in a similar manner. Results from the Kansas field study indicated that the ratio of eddy diffusivities of heat and momentum was approximately 1.35 under neutral conditions. A similar experiment was conducted in a flat field in northwestern Minnesota in 1973. This experiment used both ground and balloon-based observations of the surface layer and further validated the theoretical predictions from similarity.<ref name=k76>{{cite journal|last=Kaimal|first=J. C.|author2=J. C. Wyngaard |author3=D. A. Haugen |author4=O. R. Cot\u00e9 |author5=Y. Izumi |author6=S. J. Caughey |author7=C. J. Readings |title=Turbulence Structure in the Convective Boundary Layer|journal=Journal of the Atmospheric Sciences|date=1976|volume=33|issue=11|pages=2152\u20132169|bibcode = 1976JAtS...33.2152K |doi = 10.1175/1520-0469(1976)033<2152:TSITCB>2.0.CO;2 }}</ref>\n\n=== In large eddy simulations ===\nIn addition to field experiments, analysis of M\u2013O similarity theory can be conducted using high-resolution [[large eddy simulation]]s. The simulation indicates that the temperature field agrees well with M\u2013O similarity. However, the velocity field shows significant anomalies from M\u2013O similarity.<ref name=les_mo>{{cite journal|last1=Khanna|first1=Samir|last2=Brasseur|first2=James G.|title=Analysis of Monin\u2013Obukhov similarity from large-eddy simulation|journal=J. Fluid Mech.|date=1997|volume=345|issue=1|pages=251\u2013286|bibcode = 1997JFM...345..251K }}</ref>\n\n== Limitations ==\nM\u2013O similarity theory, albeit successful for surface layers from experimental validations, is essentially a diagnostic empirical theory based upon local first order turbulence closure. Typically, 10%~20% errors are associated with the universal functions. When applied to a vegetated areas or complex terrains, it can result in large discrepancies. Because universal functions are often determined under dry conditions, the applicability of M\u2013O similarity theory under moist conditions were not well studied.\n\nBasic parameter set of the M\u2013O similarity theory includes buoyancy production <math>\\dfrac{gQ}{T}</math>. It is argued that with such parameter set, the scaling is applied to the integral features of the flow, whereas an eddy specific similarity relationship prefers the usage of energy [[dissipation]] rate <math>\\epsilon_0</math>.<ref name=m09>{{cite journal|last=McNaughton|first=Keith|title=The rise and fall of Monin-Obukhov theory|journal=AsiaFlux Newsletter|date=2009|issue=30|pages=1\u20134|url=http://www.mcnaughty.com/keith/papers/Rise_and_Fall_of_MOST.pdf}}</ref> This scheme is able to explain anomalies of M\u2013O similarity theory, but involves non-locality to modeling and experiments.\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Monin\u2013Obukhov length|Obukhov length]]\n*[[Surface layer]]\n*[[Log wind profile|Logarithmic wind profile]]\n*[[Mixing length model]]\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Monin-Obukhov similarity theory}}\n[[Category:Dimensional analysis]]\n[[Category:Physics theorems]]\n", "name_user": "Mucmhk3", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eValidations:I replaced the previous image, which was a photo of grass, labeled as wheat. The replacement photo shows actual wheat.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monin%E2%80%93Obukhov_similarity_theory"}
{"title_page": "White Hall State Historic Site", "text_new": "{{Infobox NRHP\n  | name = Whitehall\n  | nrhp_type = \n  | image = White Hall Mansion.jpg\n  | caption = White Hall in 2009\n  | location = 500 White Hall Shrine Road\n  | nearest_city= [[Richmond, Kentucky]]\n  | coordinates = {{coord|37|49|58|N|84|21|8|W|region:US_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = Kentucky#USA\n  | built = 1798\n  | architect = Gen. Green Clay; Thomas Lewinski\n  | architecture = Italianate, Georgian\n  | added = March 11, 1971\n  | area = {{convert|13.6|acre}}\n  | refnum = 71000352<ref name=nris>{{NRISref|2009a}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''White Hall State Historic Site''' is a {{convert|14|acre|sing=on}} park in [[Richmond, Kentucky]], southeast of [[Lexington, Kentucky|Lexington]].\n\n==White Hall==\nThe site's major feature is White Hall, the home of [[Kentucky]] legislator [[Cassius Marcellus Clay (1810\u20131903)|Cassius Marcellus Clay]] and Mary Jane Warfield Clay.  He was an [[abolitionism in the United States|anti-slavery]] newspaper publisher, politician, soldier and Minister to [[Russia]] through the Lincoln, Johnson and Grant administrations. He published ''True American'' for nearly 25 years.\n\nThis restored 44-room [[Italianate]] began as a 7-room structure built in 1798-1799 by General Green Clay. It was expanded and remodeled in the early 1860s to the structure seen today.\n\nThe site became part of the state park system in 1968.<ref name=kye>{{cite book |editor=Kleber, John E. |others=Associate editors: [[Thomas D. Clark]], Lowell H. Harrison, and James C. Klotter |title=The Kentucky Encyclopedia |year=1992 |publisher=The University Press of Kentucky |location=Lexington, Kentucky |isbn=0-8131-1772-0 |chapter=Historic Sites}}</ref>\n\nOn April 12, 2011 White Hall was designated as a national historic site in journalism by the Society of Professional Journalists, because of Clay's career as a publisher.<ref>[http://www.eku.edu/news/spj-dedicates-white-hall-historic-site-journalism \"Dedicates White Hall as Historic Site in Journalism\"], Eastern Kentucky University</ref>\n\n==Restoration== \nThe house's restoration was completed and open to the public in 1971 under the leadership of Kentucky's First Lady [[Beula C. Nunn]], with assistance of the Kentucky Mansions Preservation Foundation.<ref>https://www.flickr.com/photos/bearsite/5501419050/</ref> In addition to the heirloom and period furnishings, White Hall has many unique features for its day, including indoor plumbing and central heating.<ref>http://parks.ky.gov/statehistoricsites/wh/index.htm</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|White Hall (Kentucky)}}\n*[https://parks.ky.gov/richmond/trails/trails/white-hall-historic-site White Hall State Historic Site] Kentucky Department of Parks\n* [https://www.flickr.com/photos/bearsite/5501419050/ Photo of White Hall]\n* [https://www.flickr.com/photos/bearsite/5500830611/in/photostream/ Photo of White Hall's stone kitchen building]\n\n{{Kentucky Parks}}\n{{National Register of Historic Places}}\n\n[[Category:Kentucky State Historic Sites]]\n[[Category:Protected areas of Madison County, Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Houses in Madison County, Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Museums in Madison County, Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Historic house museums in Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Houses on the National Register of Historic Places in Kentucky]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Madison County, Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Italianate architecture in Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Georgian architecture in Kentucky]]\n[[Category:1968 establishments in Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Houses completed in 1798]]\n[[Category:Protected areas established in 1968]]\n[[Category:Green Clay family]]\n[[Category:Plantations in Kentucky]]\n\n\n{{Kentucky-NRHP-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox NRHP\n  | name = Whitehall\n  | nrhp_type = \n  | image = White Hall Mansion.jpg\n  | caption = White Hall in 2009\n  | location = 500 White Hall Shrine Road\n  | nearest_city= [[Richmond, Kentucky]]\n  | coordinates = {{coord|37|49|58|N|84|21|8|W|region:US_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = Kentucky#USA\n  | built = 1798\n  | architect = Gen. Green Clay; Thomas Lewinski\n  | architecture = Italianate, Georgian\n  | added = March 11, 1971\n  | area = {{convert|13.6|acre}}\n  | refnum = 71000352<ref name=nris>{{NRISref|2009a}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''White Hall State Historic Site''' is a {{convert|14|acre|sing=on}} park in [[Richmond, Kentucky]], southeast of [[Lexington, Kentucky|Lexington]].\n\n==White Hall==\nThe site's major feature is White Hall, the home of [[Kentucky]] legislator [[Cassius Marcellus Clay (1810\u20131903)|Cassius Marcellus Clay]] and Mary Jane Warfield Clay.  He was an [[abolitionism in the United States|anti-slavery]] newspaper publisher, politician, soldier and Minister to [[Russia]] through the Lincoln, Johnson and Grant administrations. He published ''True American'' for nearly 25 years.\n\nThis restored 44-room [[Italianate]] began as a 7-room structure built in 1798-1799 by General Green Clay. It was expanded and remodeled in the early 1860s to the structure seen today.\n\nThe site became part of the state park system in 1968.<ref name=kye>{{cite book |editor=Kleber, John E. |others=Associate editors: [[Thomas D. Clark]], Lowell H. Harrison, and James C. Klotter |title=The Kentucky Encyclopedia |year=1992 |publisher=The University Press of Kentucky |location=Lexington, Kentucky |isbn=0-8131-1772-0 |chapter=Historic Sites}}</ref>\n\nOn April 12, 2011 White Hall was designated as a national historic site in journalism by the Society of Professional Journalists, because of Clay's career as a publisher.<ref>[http://www.eku.edu/news/spj-dedicates-white-hall-historic-site-journalism \"Dedicates White Hall as Historic Site in Journalism\"], Eastern Kentucky University</ref>\n\n==Restoration== \nThe house's restoration was completed and open to the public in 1971 under the leadership of Kentucky's First Lady [[Beula C. Nunn]], with assistance of the Kentucky Mansions Preservation Foundation.<ref>https://www.flickr.com/photos/bearsite/5501419050/</ref> In addition to the heirloom and period furnishings, White Hall has many unique features for its day, including indoor plumbing and central heating.<ref>http://parks.ky.gov/statehistoricsites/wh/index.htm</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|White Hall (Kentucky)}}\n*[http://parks.ky.gov/parks/historicsites/white-hall/default.aspx White Hall State Historic Site] Kentucky Department of Parks\n* [https://www.flickr.com/photos/bearsite/5501419050/ Photo of White Hall]\n* [https://www.flickr.com/photos/bearsite/5500830611/in/photostream/ Photo of White Hall's stone kitchen building]\n\n{{Kentucky Parks}}\n{{National Register of Historic Places}}\n\n[[Category:Kentucky State Historic Sites]]\n[[Category:Protected areas of Madison County, Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Houses in Madison County, Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Museums in Madison County, Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Historic house museums in Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Houses on the National Register of Historic Places in Kentucky]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Madison County, Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Italianate architecture in Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Georgian architecture in Kentucky]]\n[[Category:1968 establishments in Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Houses completed in 1798]]\n[[Category:Protected areas established in 1968]]\n[[Category:Green Clay family]]\n[[Category:Plantations in Kentucky]]\n\n\n{{Kentucky-NRHP-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Charles Wilton", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/White_Hall_State_Historic_Site"}
{"title_page": "University of Arizona", "text_new": "{{distinguish | Arizona State University}}\n{{short description|Public university in Tucson, Arizona, United States}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name = University of Arizona\n| image_name = \n| image_upright = 0.7\n| latin_name = Universitas Arizonensis\n| motto = \"[[Bear Down|weirdos Arizona]]\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://wc.arizona.edu/papers/98/214/01_8.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060912092852/http://wc.arizona.edu/papers/98/214/01_8.html|archivedate=September 12, 2006|title=It's music to Wildcat alumni's ears|newspaper=[[Arizona Daily Wildcat]] |date=November 4, 2005|quote='Bear Down, Arizona' has become the school's motto and second fight song since the death of the man who first uttered the words 'bear down' in 1926.}}</ref><br />The seal of the university is emblazoned with the word \"Sursum\", Latin for \"Upwards\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.inewidea.com/db/77289057.html|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130126054907/http://www.inewidea.com/db/77289057.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2013-01-26|title=The Logo of the University of Arizona}}</ref>\n| established = Chartered {{start date and age|1885}}\n| type = [[Public university|Public]] [[research university]]\n| academic_affiliations = [[Association of American Universities|AAU]]\n| endowment = $1 (2019)<ref>As of June 30, 2019. {{cite web |url=https://www.nacubo.org/Research/2019/Public-NTSE-Tables|title=U.S. and Canadian 2019 NTSE Participating Institutions Listed by Fiscal Year 2019 Endowment Market Value, Percentage Change in Market Value from FY18 to FY19, and FY19 Endowment Market Values Per Full-time Equivalent Student (Excel) |publisher=National Association of College and University Business Officers and TIAA |access-date=February 2, 2020}}</ref>\n| president = [[Robert C. Robbins]]<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite news|url=https://uanews.arizona.edu/story/regents-announce-robbins-finalist-ua-presidency|title=Regents Announce Robbins as Finalist for UA Presidency|work=UANews|access-date=April 7, 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n| students = 45,918 (2019)<ref name=\"Facts\">{{cite web |url=https://uair.arizona.edu/content/enrollment |title=Enrollment |publisher=University of Arizona |access-date=December 2, 2019}}</ref>\n| undergrad = 35,801 (2019)<ref name=\"Facts\"/>\n| postgrad = 10,117 (2019)<ref name=\"Facts\"/>\n| faculty = 3,534 (2017)<ref>{{cite web| url=http://factbook.arizona.edu/2017-18/employees |title=Employee Headcounts|work=2017-2018 Factbook|publisher=University of Arizona|date=2018}}</ref>\n| city = [[Tucson, Arizona|Tucson]]\n| state = [[Arizona]]\n| country = United States\n| campus = Urban, {{convert|380|acre|km2|1}}\n| colors = Cardinal Red and Navy Blue<ref>{{cite web|url=https://licensing.arizona.edu/logo-sheet-0|title=Logo Sheet {{!}} Trademarks and Licensing {{!}} The University of Arizona|date=December 9, 2013|access-date=May 17, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171112021417/https://licensing.arizona.edu/logo-sheet-0 |archive-date=November 12, 2017}}</ref><br />{{college color boxes|Arizona Wildcats}}\n| nickname = [[Arizona Wildcats|Wildcats]]\n| sporting_affiliations = [[NCAA Division I FBS]] \u2013 [[Pac-12 Conference|Pac-12]] and [[Mountain Pacific Sports Federation|MPSF]]\n| website = \n| logo = pitch fork\n| mascots = [[Wilbur and Wilma]]\n| logo_size = 200\n}}\n[[File:University of Arizona May 2019 09 (Old Main).jpg|thumb|The \"Old Main\", also known as the \"University of Arizona School of Agriculture\". It was added to the National Register of Historic Places in 1972, ref. : #72000199.]]\n\nThe '''University of Arizona''' ('''Arizona''', '''U of A''', '''UArizona''', or '''UA''') is a [[Public university|public]] [[research university]] in [[Tucson, Arizona]]. Founded in 1885, the UofA was the first university in the [[Arizona Territory]]. {{as of|2018}}, the university enrolls 45,217 students<ref name=\"Facts\"/> in 19 separate colleges/schools, including the [[University of Arizona College of Medicine]] in Tucson and Phoenix and the [[James E. Rogers College of Law]], and is affiliated with two academic medical centers ([[Banner University Medical Center Tucson|Banner - University Medical Center Tucson]] and Banner - University Medical Center Phoenix). The University of Arizona is governed by the [[Arizona Board of Regents]]. The University of Arizona is one of the elected members of the [[Association of American Universities]] and is the only representative from the state of Arizona to this group.\n\nKnown as the [[Arizona Wildcats]] (often shortened to \"Cats\"), the UA's intercollegiate athletic teams are members of the [[Pac-12 Conference]] of the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]]. UA athletes have won national titles in several sports, most notably men's basketball, baseball, and softball. The official colors of the university and its athletic teams are cardinal red and navy blue.\n\n==History==\n{{expand section|date=March 2014}}\n[[File:OldMain UofA 1889.jpg|thumb|left|Old Main in 1889]]\nAfter the passage of the [[Morrill Land-Grant Acts|Morrill Land-Grant Act of 1862]], the push for a university in Arizona grew. The Arizona Territory's \"[[Thieving Thirteenth]]\" Legislature approved the University of Arizona in 1885 and selected the city of Tucson to receive the appropriation to build the university. Tucson hoped to receive the appropriation for the territory's mental hospital, which carried a $100,000 allocation instead of the $25,000 allotted to the territory's only university (Arizona State University was also chartered in 1885, but it was created as Arizona's [[normal school]], and not a university).{{citation needed|date=February 2017}} Flooding on the [[Salt River (Arizona)|Salt River]] delayed Tucson's legislators, and by they time they reached [[Prescott, Arizona|Prescott]], back-room deals allocating the most desirable territorial institutions had been made. Tucson was largely disappointed with receiving what was viewed as an inferior prize. With no parties willing to provide land for the new institution, the citizens of Tucson prepared to return the money to the Territorial Legislature until two gamblers and a saloon keeper decided to donate the land to build the school.<ref name=\"History 3a\">{{cite web | title=The Founding of the University: Myths and Heroes| access-date=Aug 11, 2019 | url=https://uanews.arizona.edu/story/the-founding-of-the-university-myths-and-heroes}}</ref> Construction of [[Old Main, University of Arizona|Old Main]], the first building on campus, began on October 27, 1887, and classes met for the first time in 1891 with 32 students in Old Main, which is still in use today.<ref name=\"History 3\">{{cite web | title=The Old Main | publisher=Arizona Board of Regents | year=2005 | work=UA History | access-date=March 29, 2006 | url=http://www.arizona.edu/tours/history/history3.php |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20060211105338/http://www.arizona.edu/tours/history/history3.php <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = February 11, 2006}}</ref> Because there were no high schools in Arizona Territory, the university maintained separate preparatory classes for the first 23 years of operation.{{citation needed|date=April 2019}}\n\n==Academics==\nThe University of Arizona offers bachelor's, master's, doctoral, and professional degrees. Grades are given on a strict 4-point scale with \"A\" worth 4, \"B\" worth 3, \"C\" worth 2, \"D\" worth 1 and \"E\" worth zero points.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://registrar.arizona.edu/grades/university-grading-systems|title=University Grading Systems {{!}} Office of The Registrar|website=registrar.arizona.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-01-06}}</ref>\n\n===Rankings===\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n{{Infobox US university ranking\n| ARWU_N = 46-58\n| ARWU_W = 101\u2013150\n| Wamo_NU = 92\n| USNWR_NU = 117\n| USNWR_W = 85\n| QS_W = 262\n| THE_WSJ = 136\n| THES_W = 104\n| Forbes = 218\n}}\n{{col-break}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable collapsible collapsed\" style=\"float:right\" \"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! colspan=4 style=\"{{CollegePrimaryStyle|University of Arizona Wildcats|color=blue}}\" |National Program Rankings<ref name=\"USNWR Grad School Rankings\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.usnews.com/best-graduate-schools/university-of-arizona-104179/overall-rankings|title=University of Arizona Graduate School rankings|magazine=U.S. News & World Report|access-date=July 30, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n! Program\n! Ranking\n|-\n| Audiology || 9\n|-\n| Biological Sciences || 46\n|-\n| Business || 52\n|-\n| Chemistry || 41\n|-\n| Clinical Psychology || 31\n|-\n| Computer Science || 43\n|-\n| Earth Sciences || 8\n|-\n| Economics || 42\n|-\n| Education || 64\n|-\n| Engineering || 64\n|-\n| English || 77\n|-\n| Fine Arts || 55\n|-\n| History || 63\n|-\n| Law || 39\n|-\n| Library & Information Studies || 22\n|-\n| Mathematics || 47\n|-\n| Medicine: Primary Care || 62\n|-\n| Medicine: Research || 65\n|-\n| Nursing: Master's || 30\n|-\n| Physics || 37\n|-\n| Political Science || 51\n|-\n| Psychology || 45\n|-\n| Public Affairs || 35\n|-\n| Public Health || 32\n|-\n| Rehabilitation Counseling || 4\n|-\n| Sociology || 24\n|-\n| Speech-Language Pathology || 7\n|}\n{{col-break}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable collapsible collapsed\" style=\"float:right\" \"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! colspan=4 style=\"{{CollegePrimaryStyle|University of Arizona Wildcats|color=blue}}\" |Global Program Rankings<ref name=\"USNWR Global Univ Rankings\">{{cite magazine|title=U.S. News Best Global Universities Rankings|magazine=U.S. News & World Report|access-date=July 30, 2019|url=https://www.usnews.com/education/best-global-universities/university-of-arizona-104179/overall-rankings|date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190411120553/https://www.usnews.com/education/best-global-universities/university-of-arizona-104179/overall-rankings|a