{"title_page": "Graham Dudman", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2016}}\n'''Graham Dudman''' (born 2 October 1963) is the current Managing Editor of ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'' newspaper.<ref>{{cite web|title=Graham Dudman , Esq Authorised Biography |url=http://www.debretts.com/people/biographies/browse/d/19696/Graham%20Michael+DUDMAN.aspx |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120731141638/http://www.debretts.com/people/biographies/browse/d/19696/Graham%20Michael+DUDMAN.aspx |url-status=dead |archive-date=31 July 2012 |work=Debrett's People of Today |accessdate=18 July 2010 }}</ref>\n\nOn 28 January 2012, the [[BBC]] said it understood Dudman had been arrested in relation to the [[News International phone hacking scandal]], by detectives investigating payments made to police by journalists.<ref>{{cite news|title=Operation Elveden: Five held in police payment probe|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-16771809|accessdate=28 January 2012|newspaper=BBC News|location=London|date=28 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2014, Dudman's trial on four charges of conspiring to commit misconduct in a public office began, along with that of five other senior staff and journalists at ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'' newspaper. The trial related to illegal payments allegedly made to public officials, with prosecutors saying Dudman and the co-accused conspired to pay officials including police, prison officers and soldiers from 2002\u201311. Specifically, Dudman and his co-defendants faced accusations of buying confidential information about the Royal Family, celebrities and prison inmates. They all denied the charges.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-29645621|title=Sun staff made illegal payments on 'grand scale', court hears|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=16 October 2014 |website=BBC News | accessdate=16 October 2014}}</ref> On 17 April 2015, the [[Crown Prosecution Service]] announced that charges against Dudman over alleged payments to officials were to be dropped.<ref name=\"BBC News 17 April 2015\">{{cite web | title= Operation Elveden: Nine journalists have cases dropped |url= http://m.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-32355478| author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|date= 17 April 2015 | website= BBC News | accessdate= 17 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dudman, Graham}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:British male journalists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:The Sun (United Kingdom) people]]\n\n\n{{UK-journalist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2016}}\n'''Graham Dudman''' (born 2 October 1963) is the current Managing Editor of ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'' newspaper.<ref>{{cite web|title=Graham Dudman , Esq Authorised Biography |url=http://www.debretts.com/people/biographies/browse/d/19696/Graham%20Michael+DUDMAN.aspx |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120731141638/http://www.debretts.com/people/biographies/browse/d/19696/Graham%20Michael+DUDMAN.aspx |url-status=dead |archive-date=31 July 2012 |work=Debrett's People of Today |accessdate=18 July 2010 }}</ref>\n\nOn 28 January 2012, the [[BBC]] said it understood Dudman had been arrested in relation to the [[News International phone hacking scandal]], by detectives investigating payments made to police by journalists.<ref>{{cite news|title=Operation Elveden: Five held in police payment probe|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-16771809|accessdate=28 January 2012|newspaper=BBC News|location=London|date=28 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2014, Dudman's trial on four charges of conspiring to commit misconduct in a public office began, along with that of five other senior staff and journalists at ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'' newspaper. The trial related to illegal payments allegedly made to public officials, with prosecutors saying Dudman and the co-accused conspired to pay officials including police, prison officers and soldiers from 2002\u201311. Specifically, Dudman and his co-defendants faced accusations of buying confidential information about the Royal Family, celebrities and prison inmates. They all denied the charges.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-29645621|title=Sun staff made illegal payments on 'grand scale', court hears|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=16 October 2014 |website=BBC News | accessdate=16 October 2014}}</ref> On 17 April 2015, the [[Crown Prosecution Service]] announced that charges against Dudman over alleged payments to officials were to be dropped.<ref name=\"BBC News 17 April 2015\">{{cite web | title= Operation Elveden: Nine journalists have cases dropped |url= http://m.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-32355478| author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|date= 17 April 2015 | website= BBC News | accessdate= 17 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dudman, Graham}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:British male journalists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:The Sun (United Kingdom) people]]\n\n\n{{UK-journalist-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Graham_Dudman"}
